						<!-- firstHeading -->
			<h1 id="firstHeading" class="firstHeading" lang="en"><span dir="auto">Stone (unit)</span></h1>
			<!-- /firstHeading -->
			<!-- bodyContent -->
			<div id="bodyContent">
								<!-- tagline -->
				<div id="siteSub">From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia</div>
				<!-- /tagline -->
								<!-- subtitle -->
				<div id="contentSub">  (Redirected from <a href="../../w/index-title=Stone_(mass)&redirect=no.php.html" title="Stone (mass)">Stone (mass)</a>)</div>
				<!-- /subtitle -->
																<!-- jumpto -->
				<div id="jump-to-nav" class="mw-jump">
					Jump to:					<a href="#mw-head">navigation</a>, 					<a href="#p-search">search</a>
				</div>
				<!-- /jumpto -->
								<!-- bodycontent -->
				<div id="mw-content-text" lang="en" dir="ltr" class="mw-content-ltr"><div class="dablink">This article is about the European unit of weight. For Asian uses of 'stone', see <a href="Picul" title="Picul">Picul</a>.</div>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Fotothek_df_tg_0000212_Waage.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/2c/Fotothek_df_tg_0000212_Waage.jpg/220px-Fotothek_df_tg_0000212_Waage.jpg" width="220" height="158" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/2c/Fotothek_df_tg_0000212_Waage.jpg/330px-Fotothek_df_tg_0000212_Waage.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/2c/Fotothek_df_tg_0000212_Waage.jpg/440px-Fotothek_df_tg_0000212_Waage.jpg 2x" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Fotothek_df_tg_0000212_Waage.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"><img src="http://bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf8/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png" width="15" height="11" alt="" /></a></div>
German medieval scale for weighting bales of wool. The unit of measure was the local stone.</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>The <b>stone</b> (abbreviation <i>st</i><sup id="cite_ref-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-1"><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup>) is an informal <a href="Units_of_measurement" title="Units of measurement">unit of measure</a> equal to 14 <a href="Pound_(mass)#Avoirdupois_pound" title="Pound (mass)">pounds avoirdupois</a> (about 6.35&#160;kg<sup id="cite_ref-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-4"><span>[</span>nb 1<span>]</span></a></sup>) used in Great Britain and Ireland for measuring human <a href="Body_weight" title="Body weight">body weight</a>. The stone was formerly used for purposes of trade in many North-West European countries where its value ranged from about 5 to 40 <a href="Pound_(mass)#Historic_use" title="Pound (mass)">local pounds</a> (3 to 15&#160;kg), but with the advent of <a href="Metrication" title="Metrication">metrication</a> from the mid-19th century onwards it was superseded by the <a href="Kilogram" title="Kilogram">kilogram</a>; its use for trade in the United Kingdom and in Ireland being rescinded in the 1980s.</p>
<table id="toc" class="toc">
<tr>
<td>
